descript.abstract: 1:24,000 scale GIS dataset containing hydrographic features for Colorado and Colorado Division of Wildlife (CDOW) aquatic management codes.
descript.purpose: Provide a GIS dataset containing Colorado's hydrographic features to store CDOW aquatic management codes. This dataset is intended to be an interim product for use by CDOW staff until such time the 1:24,000 scale NHD for Colorado data is complete and CDOW has transferred its aquatic management codes to it.
descript.supplinf:
1:24000 scale, statewide, stream network features.
All CDOW managed waters may not be represented herein. At last count less than 1% was unmapped.
Data Sources: 1:24K USGS DRGs.
NOTE: You may notice gaps between stream network segments. These are most likely due to the intersection with a ditch. A resource to check this is the 1:24,000 scale DRG.
Feature Items- Arcs: FEATURE, CODE, CODE2, DOW_NAME, DOW_NAME2, NAME1, NAME2, STRAHLER, HYDROCODE, QUADCODE, SOURCE, AREA_BIO, FEATURE1, CONDITION1, TYPE1, SURFACE1, CONST_MAT1, UNDERP1, BRAID, FEATURE2, CONDITION2, TYPE2, SURFACE2, CONST_MAT2, UNDERP2.
FEATURE. This attribute was created to simplify feature type. It was created by combining several fields which have been omitted in this version of the dataset.
This may include - Artificial Flow Path (used to show network connectivity through polygonal features), Ditch, Intermittent Stream, Perennial Stream, Pipeline, Polygonal Feature Limit (denotes a border of a polygonal feature that is not actually a shoreline, such as the edge of a sandy wash or the maximum extent of an ice mass), Shoreline, Stream Connector.
CODE. CDOW water codes for managed streams.
DOW_NAME. This is the feature name found in the CDOW aquatic database.
NAME. This is the feature name modified for cartographic purposes.
STRAHLER. Stream order was calculated using the Strahler stream-ordering method. It was only applied to natural streams and associated artificial flow paths and on a case by case basis to ditches that maintained stream connectivity.
HYDROCODE. Delineates the eight digit hydro unit code in which the stream arc segment falls.
QUADCODE. Delineates the topographic Quad number in which the stream arc segment falls.
SOURCE. CDOW, CFF or DLG-3.
AREA_BIO. This field identifies the initials of the CDOW area biologist charged with managing the particular water.
Arc attributes: STREAM arcs have a defining attribute of FEATURE1 = 1. A stream can be perennial or intermittent and defined as a connector, underpass, or braid. A Perennial Stream is identified by CONDITION1 = 1 while an Intermittent Stream is identified by CONDITION1 = 2. A stream with the attribute TYPE1 = 88 identifies a Stream Connector. Connectors are features that are added to supplement existing voids in the data for downstream features. They are added so that they conform to natural features and contour lines. Stream to stream connecting features must be within 800 meters of each other. Stream to lake, or lake to lake connectors are added on a case-by-case basis to maintain the known connectivity of the hydro network. Connectors can be added through dams. Connectors are NOT added from stream to ditch, ditch to stream, after an intentional stream termination or when there are intentional breaks from stream diversions into ditch/canals. A stream with the attribute UNDERP1 = 1 identifies an underpass in which a stream segment passes under a flume. A stream with the attribute BRAID = 1 identifies a stream braid. When a stream forks downstream the braid attribute is assigned to the shortest and most insignificant fork. Only one stream of the fork is assigned the braid attribute. When a braided stream joins with another inflowing stream the new stream created does NOT get a braid attribute.
DITCHES and PIPELINES are generally excluded from this stream ordered statewide network, unless they were pertinent to continuity of the stream network which was determined on an individual basis. Ditch arcs have a defining attribute of FEATURE1 = 2. A ditch is a feature which breaks the contours, does not follow a natural stream channel, and identified on the map as a ditch, flume, or abandoned aqueduct. A ditch segment with the attribute TYPE1 = 12 identifies a Flume. Flumes occur within both streams and ditches and flow over streams, ditches, pipelines and other water features. A stream, artificial flow path, ditch, or pipeline can flow into or out of a flume. A ditch segment that intersects a flume is attributed with UNDERP1 = 1. Abandoned aqueducts denoted by long dashed lines on the map are coded as ditches. Connectors are NOT added to maintain the connectivity of ditches. Ditches do NOT get a braid attribute. Pipeline arcs have a defining attribute of FEATURE1 = 3. A pipeline is a feature which breaks the contours, does not follow a natural stream channel, and identified on the map as an aqueduct, tunnel, penstock, or siphon. A pipeline with the attribute TYPE1 = 3 identifies an aqueduct. An aqueduct flows below the surface and is always attributed with SURFACE1 = 2. A tunnel is a pipeline with the attribute TYPE1 = 4. An elevated tunnel is identified by SURFACE1 = 1. A pipeline with TYPE1 = 6 is a penstock. A siphon is identified by TYPE1 = 5. Siphons flow under streams, ditches, pipelines, and non-water features. Water features that intersect siphons do not get special coding. Pipelines the intersect flumes are attributed with UNDERP1 = 1. All dashed short blue lines on the map that are not labeled as a tunnel or aqueduct are attributed as pipelines with a SURFACE1 = 2. These unidentified pipelines are often flowing out of lakes or ponds. Connectors are NOT added to maintain the connectivity of pipelines. Pipelines do NOT get a braid attribute.
ARTIFIAL FLOW PATH (AFP's) arcs have a defining attribute of FEATURE1 = 4. Artificial flow paths are used to maintain the connectivity of water flow. All water features that flow into, out of, or through polygonal water bodies have a connecting AFP. More than one AFP can be found in a water body connecting all inflowing streams to the main flow artery. All head water bodies connecting an out-flowing feature have an AFP. All terminating water bodies connecting an inflowing water feature have an AFP. Artificial flow paths are used in washes and marshes to maintain connectivity when a stream would most likely flow through the water body. If a stream is delineated on the map in awash, marsh, or inundation area the stream is left as is and AFP's are used to fill in the flow gaps. Artificial flow paths that fork downstream are considered braids. Only one of the forks receives a braid attribute BRAID = 1. AFP's connecting to ditches can also receive a braid attribute. AFP's that intersect flumes are attributed with UNDERP1 = 1. AFP's are NOT found outside of a polygonal water body. Artificial flow paths are never attributed as connectors but can be used to maintain the flow of a connector. Artificial flow paths are NOT used to maintain flow through dams. AFP's are NOT found in free standing polygonal water bodies.
POLYGONAL FEATURE LIMIT arcs have a defining attribute of FEATURE1 = 22. These will only occur as a secondary feature coincident with a stream network arc. Polygonal feature limits are boundaries for Ditches, Washes, Marshes, Ice Masses, Non-Lake Reservoirs, Playas, Inundation Areas, Dams, or Non-Descriptive. A polygonal ditch is identified by TYPE1 = 52. A polygonal wash is identified by TYPE1 = 54. A polygonal marsh is identified by TYPE1 = 55. A polygonal ice mass is identified by TYPE1 = 56. A polygonal non-lake reservoir is identified by TYPE1 = 58. Non-lake reservoirs are identified on the map or delineated with a black line. A polygonal playa is identified by TYPE1 = 59. A polygonal inundation area is identified by TYPE1 = 60. A polygonal dam is identified by TYPE1 = 61. Polygonal dams are delineated following the modified contours or black lines on the map. A polygonal segment with TYPE1 = 99 is considered a non-descriptive boundary. Non-descriptive boundaries are used to separate features when there is no defining boundary present on the map. For example, non-descriptive boundaries can be use as a boundary between a lake and polygonal stream, lake and a spillway, different named areas of one water feature, two polygonal streams that share a shoreline, a polygonal stream and an out flowing canal, or to contain a polygonal feature that crosses a defined boundary such as a watershed or state border.
DOUBLE ATTRIBUTING is applied to arcs that separate adjacent polygonal features. Arcs that are double attributed have a second set of attributes denoted by a '2' after the name of the item. For example, when a stream and a marsh share a boundary the arc will be coded as FEATURE1 = 1, FEATURE2 = 22 and TYPE2 = 55. When a perennial stream and a wash share a boundary the arc will be coded as FEATURE1 = 1, CONDITION1 = 2, FEATURE2 = 22 and TYPE2 = 54. In each case the second set of attributes follow the same rules as the first set of attributes. NAMES of arc water features are determined by what is named on the map. If a name is present it is attributed as NAME1 = (name on the map). In some cases the use of USGS GNISID name points were used to determine the extent of the stream name and to which forks the name applies. Names beginning with 'Mc' were changed so that there are no spaces in the name. For example, Mc Kenna Creek is changed to McKenna Creek. Streams, ditches, pipelines, linear dams, and artificial flow paths are the only arc features that carry a name attribute. When a water feature has more than one name the least significant name is applied to the second attributing scheme. The second attribute scheme does NOT have to be populated with any other attributes if the water feature is the same. Artificial flow paths carry the stream, ditch, or canal name through lakes and polygonal water bodies. Headwater lake AFPs are NOT named. Features with a BRAID = 1 are NOT named unless it is unavoidable. Valleys and meadows, and other land features are NOT named.

sngdate.caldate: Features may be only as current as the date of the corresponding 7.5 minute USGS topo quad. However, many features have been digitized from DOQs, DOW paper maps and other sources.
